This is a known breaking change. Android 15 (API 35), which .NET 10 targets, deprecated `adjustResize` and enforces **edge-to-edge** rendering. You now need to react to **window insets** instead.

## Two options:

### 1. Quick fix — use `adjustPan`
In `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`, set the soft input mode:

```csharp
[Activity(WindowSoftInputMode = SoftInput.AdjustPan, ...)]
public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity { }
```

This pans the whole view up. Simple but less polished — your toolbar scrolls off-screen.

### 2. Recommended — handle IME insets

In `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`, listen for keyboard insets and apply bottom padding:

```csharp
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using AndroidX.Core.Graphics;

protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
{
    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

    var content = FindViewById(Android.Resource.Id.Content)!;

    ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(content, new KeyboardInsetsListener());
}

private class KeyboardInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
{
    public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
    {
        var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
        var navInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

        // Use whichever is taller — keyboard or nav bar
        int bottom = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navInsets.Bottom);
        v.SetPadding(0, 0, 0, bottom);

        return insets;
    }
}
```

This keeps your toolbar visible and slides only the input bar up by exactly the keyboard height. No changes needed in your XAML layout.
